Security & Encryption Guidance

Always use TLS (HTTPS) for all traffic.

Encrypt user passwords using bcrypt / Argon2.

Encrypt sensitive files at rest using server-side encryption (AES-256) and store keys in a secrets manager.

End-to-End Encryption option (recommended for client assets):

Use Web Crypto API on the client to generate a symmetric key for each project. The client encrypts files before upload; server stores encrypted blobs.

Private keys remain with the client (or shared with authorized staff via an encrypted key exchange). Store only encrypted keys server-side.

Document tradeoffs: E2EE prevents server-side indexing/processing (e.g., no server-side previews or text extraction) unless users permit decryption.

Protect API endpoints with proper authentication & authorization.

Rate limiting, input validation, and OWASP Top 10 mitigations.

Technical Stack (recommended)

Frontend

Framework: Next.js with TypeScript (supports SSR, SSG, incremental static regeneration)

Styling: Tailwind CSS (utility-first) or Tailwind + CSS variables for brand tokens

Animations: Framer Motion for polished micro-interactions; use react-intersection-observer for scroll reveals

Forms: React Hook Form + Zod for validation

Backend

Django + Django REST Framework (DRF) with PostgreSQL

Auth: Simple JWT or integrate with NextAuth for unified sessions

Background jobs: Celery + Redis (for heavy tasks: image processing, emails)

File storage: AWS S3 or DigitalOcean Spaces; serve via CDN

Optional simpler stack: Node.js (NestJS/Express) + PostgreSQL if preferred. But keep front/back separation with REST or GraphQL.

Other services

Payments: Stripe

Email: SendGrid or Mailgun

Analytics: Plausible or Google Analytics (privacy-first choice recommended)

Images: Cloudinary (auto image optimization)

CI/CD: GitHub Actions; frontend deploy to Vercel; backend to Render or AWS Elastic Beanstalk / ECS

